[[ch01-glossary]]
== Glossary and Expectations

Below are new terms and their acronyms used throughout the book.

In addition, expectations are given with respect to Old Demecracy versus New Democracy. Hopefully these expectations provide a helpful road map while reading this book.

New Democracy has little in common with world governments historically. The spirit of New Democracy is probably closer to anarchy than Old Demcracy in that there is no rule of law or government of any sort in New Democracy. As Thomas Jefferson quipped, "The government which governs least governs best because the citizens take care of themselves." New Democracy is citizens taking care of themselves  without government.  

New Democracy is of the people, by the people, and for the people, but otherwise shares nothing with Old Democracy.

The difference between New Democracy and Anarchy is that New Democracy necessarily imposes many hours per week of social service. Further New Democracy is world size society that includes everyone in the planet where Anarchy focuses on the smallest society size possible. New Democracy is a much larger proscribed burden on everyone than just voting once per year. Not so with anarchy. 

Responsibilty is the password to New Democracy where freedom is the password to Old Democracy and Anarchy.

The heart of New Democracy difference with Old Democracy is that the founders of Old Democracy  had no plan during the entire time leading up to the revolution, and only a half baked one during the revolution. And it shows today.

The Old Democracy  founders were pressed for time and in a hurry so they created a catastrophic conceit: the government  should be simple enough for everyone to understand. This conceit was needed to get it approved quickly.

New Democracy is 100% planned before we start implementing it. New Democracy requires quantum physics level intelligence to fully engage. Society is that complex. 

Do not expect to understand New Democracy. However, you very much can expect to understand your role as you will be spending hours every week implementing it. If you are able, of course.

Intuition fails at scale when systems are very large like the Earth having billions of people. However, one Intuition that does apply is that a society that eliminates the need for government can only do so with far more social resposibilty than just voting once or twice per year. It requires billions of people spending hours every week. The totality of this social work needed can not be specified in a constitution or a listing of rights. That level of effort cannot be static like a set of rights, but rather so dynamic and detailed as to take into account the unique needs of us all as we change throughout our lives.

The adoption problem I face today with New Democracy is Old Democracy defined Democracy with a Costitution that can be read in an hour. New Democracy definition can never be read because it is constantly changing faster than one can read and it has no defined set of documents. 

The expectation for any future society design is that we all need to reject  is simplicity. The simplicity of a Bill of Rights and a US Constitution. Instead our expectation is to understand our role, a role individually designed so we can understand it as our weekly work requires.

